assumptions about the thoughts and feelings of animals. Wagschal explores a number of ways in which culture and human cognition interact, including: the utility of anthropomorphism; the symbolic use of animals in medieval Christian texts; attempts at understanding the minds of animals in Spain’s early modern farming and hunting books; the effect of novelty on animal conceptualizations in "New World" histories, and how Cervantes navigated the forms of anthropomorphism that preceded him to create the first embodied animal minds in fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal psychology. 0aAnimals in literature. 0aAnimalsxSymbolic aspects. 0aAnthropomorphism in literature. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 0aLatin American literaturexHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aLiterature, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aPortuguese literaturexHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aSpanish literaturexHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aIberian.  aSpanish.  aanimal cognition.  aanimal studies.  aanthropomorphism.  acognitive historicism.  acognitive science.  aearly modern.  ahabitat.  amedieval.  amode of interaction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751770040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487517700.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles